author: Nathaniel Cline, cleveland.com
title: OHSAA Swimming and Diving 2017: Notable performances from the Division I Northeast Ohio District (video)
text:
CLEVELAND, Ohio – The Hudson girls and Solon boys swim teams were Division I Northeast District champions at Cleveland State University on Saturday. 
Hudson’s girls posted 344.5 points, ahead of runner-up North Canton Hoover (305) and Walsh Jesuit (279). 
Solon’s boys totaled 223 points, followed by Hudson (220.5) and Brecksville (214.5). 
Here are some of the notable performances from the Division I Northeast District Championships: 
Check back later for video highlights. 
BOYS 
- The Brecksville 200-yard relay team made up of David Madej, Brandon Deuch, and Jack and Pete Krusinski won with a winning time of 1:34.73. The Bees cut four seconds off their qualifying time. 
- Junior Tyler Doerrer of Green cut his qualifying time by two seconds to win the 200-yard freestyle (1:40.72). He was closely followed by Max Gustafson (1:40.83) from Shaker Heights. 
- North Royalton junior Colton Phelps came from behind to win the 200-yard individual medley (1:52.75). Phelps finished ahead of the fastest qualifier Timothy Kubacki by .4 seconds. 
- Junior Max Gustafson of Shaker Heights cut one second from his qualifying time to win the 100-yard butterfly (50.68). Solon junior Forrest Campbell finished in second by .15 seconds. 
- Brecksville junior David Madej finished a second faster than his qualifying time to win the 100-yard freestyle (44.58). Nathaniel Mullins from Hoover took second place (45.45). 
- Sophomore Eric Chimes trimmed four seconds off his qualifying time to win the 500-yard freestyle (4:40.87). The Brecksville swimmer owned the fastest time coming into the district championships. 
- Shaker Heights senior Alex Murin won the 100-yard breaststroke (58.67), besting his qualifying time by three seconds. 
- Hudson concluded the day by winning the 400-yard freestyle relay (3:09.05). The Explorers held off a closing push by Boardman (3:10.21) and Brecksville (3:10.37). 
GIRLS 
- Walsh Jesuit's 200-yard medley team made up of Hannah Gresser, Carly Hart, Emma Kaczmar and Bryanna Renuart took first with a time 1:43.71. The team broke the district record by one second. 
- Freshman Paige McCormick of Hudson put eight seconds between her and the field in the 500-yard freestyle (4:53.69). McCormick shaved off seven seconds from her qualifying time. 
- Hudson senior Natalie Gundling took first in 200-yard freestyle in 1:51.06. She was joined by sophomore teammates Maddie Hannan (1:51.38) and Gaby Palazzo (1:54.44). Gundling cut her qualifying time by seven seconds. 
- Senior Hanna Gresser of Walsh Jesuit won the 200-yard individual medley (2:01.44), breaking the district record of 2:01.80 set in 2015. Gresser also won the 100-yard breaststroke (1:01.76), bettering her own district record from last year. 
- Aurora junior Lara Ketonen trimmed two seconds off her qualifying time to win the 100-yard freestyle (51.46), finishing one-tenth second ahead of Parker Timken from Hoover. 
- Nordonia junior Christina McFarland’s time of 56.99 seconds took first in the 100-yard backstroke. 
- Hudson ended the day by winning the 400-yard freestyle relay (3:28.83), breaking the district record the school set two years ago. The Explorers trailed Walsh Jesuit midway by a body length, but closed fast on the last lap. The relay team consisted of Maddie Hannan, Paige McCormick, Natalie Gundling and Macy Trattner. Walsh Jesuit finished one second behind the Explorers. 
Results, State Swimming and Division Championships 
The OHSAA state swimming and diving championships will be held at the C.T. Branin Natatorium in Canton Feb. 22-25. 
Boys: The top two individuals/relays in each swimming event and the top seven divers go to the State Tournament at Canton. Eleven at-large swimming qualifiers will be selected on the basis of times recorded in all District Tournaments statewide. 
Girls: The top two individuals/relays in each swimming event and the top six divers to the State Tournament at Canton. Sixteen at-large swimming qualifiers will be selected on the basis of times recorded in all District Tournaments statewide.
